  fiTitle: Oliver ja aarre
  fiDesc: Pyhiinvaellus
  fiIntroText: "Nuori mies Oliver Kossler on saapunut kaukaa Suomeen. H\xE4n on kulkenut
    pitki\xE4 matkoja ja tullut v\xE4hitellen kohti pohjoista. Matkalla kulkijoilta
    h\xE4n on kuullut tarua, ett\xE4 pohjoisesta voisi l\xF6yt\xE4\xE4 aarteen. 
    \r\n\r\nH\xE4n on kuunnellut salaa kahta kulkijaa, jotka puhuvat aarteesta, jonka
    l\xF6yt\xE4\xE4 vaeltamalla pyh\xE4st\xE4 paikasta toiseen ja ker\xE4\xE4m\xE4ll\xE4
    tietoa paikan p\xE4\xE4ll\xE4. \r\n\r\nY\xF6n tullen Oliver varastaa kulkijoilta
    listan paikoista, joissa h\xE4nen pit\xE4isi k\xE4yd\xE4. Oliver kohtaa yll\xE4tyksekseen
    paljon pyhiinvaeltajia samoilla reiteill\xE4 ja alkaa v\xE4hitellen mietti\xE4,
    ett\xE4 mit\xE4 jos kysymys ei olekaan mist\xE4\xE4n maallisesta aarteesta. H\xE4n
    tuntee itsens\xE4 huijatuksi, mutta jatkaa sitke\xE4sti ja kuuntelee joka paikassa
    kerrottavia tarinoita tarkasti. \r\n\r\nToiset tarinat viev\xE4t h\xE4net kauas
    ajassa taaksep\xE4in, ja h\xE4n saa paljon ajateltavaa jokaisesta tarinasta.
    Monet kohtalot koskettavat h\xE4nt\xE4. \r\n\r\nJoidenkin mielest\xE4 h\xE4n
    ei ole oikea pyhiinvaeltaja, joidenkin mielest\xE4 h\xE4n on vasta matkansa alussa.
    Mutta sitke\xE4sti h\xE4n jatkaa eteenp\xE4in ja suorittaa h\xE4nelle annettuja
    teht\xE4vi\xE4.\r"
  fiOutroText: "Lopulta Oliver on kulkenut koko listansa loppuun. H\xE4n on kuullut
    ja n\xE4hnyt paljon, ja h\xE4n tajuaa, ett\xE4 en\xE4\xE4 ei ole tarvetta kulkea
    eteenp\xE4in. On vain tarve pys\xE4hty\xE4, olla hiljaa ja ajatella. Ei ole kiire
    en\xE4\xE4 minnek\xE4\xE4n, voi olla juuri siin\xE4 miss\xE4 on, kaikessa rauhassa
    t\xE4ss\xE4 ja nyt. Kauneuden ja pyhyyden keskell\xE4. \r\nVanha mies l\xE4hestyy
    Oliveria sen n\xE4k\xF6isen\xE4, ett\xE4 h\xE4nell\xE4 on jotain sanottavaa tai
    kysytt\xE4v\xE4\xE4.\r\n\u201DSin\xE4 olet sitten l\xF6yt\xE4nyt sen. Aarteesi.\u201D\r\nOliver
    katsoo miest\xE4 tarkemmin ja tajuaa punastuen, ett\xE4 t\xE4m\xE4 oli toinen
    niist\xE4 miehist\xE4, joilta h\xE4n varasti listan k\xE4yt\xE4vist\xE4 paikoista.\r\n\u201DEi,
    en\u201D, kielt\xE4\xE4 Oliver.\r\n\u201DMietip\xE4 uudelleen\u201D, mies sanoo
    ja istuu kaikessa rauhassa Oliverin viereen.\r\nOliver miettii ja tulee yht\xE4kki\xE4
    ajatelleeksi, ett\xE4 t\xE4m\xE4k\xF6 oli kaiken tarkoitus. \r\n\u201DOlet oikeassa\u201D,
    mies sanoi, \u201Dme n\xE4imme, ett\xE4 kaipaat rauhaa, ja sen l\xF6ysit. Todellisen
    aarteen, nauti siit\xE4 nyt rauhassa. Ja anna lista seuraavalle sit\xE4 tarvitsevalle
    parhaalla katsomallasi tavalla. \u201D\r"
  enTitle: Oliver and the treasure
  enDesc: Pilgrimage
  enIntroText: "Oliver Kossler, a young man, has travelled to Finland from afar.
    He has walked long distances gradually towards the north. On his travels, he
    has heard stories about a treasure hidden in the north.  \r\nHe has eavesdropped
    on two travellers who were talking about a treasure that you can find if you
    go from one holy place to the next collecting information on the way. \r\n\r\nAs
    the night falls, Oliver steals a list of the destinations from the two travellers.
    He is surprised to find many other pilgrims travelling the same route and, gradually,
    he begins to wonder whether there is a worldly treasure at all. He feels cheated
    but keeps on going and carefully listens to all the stories he hears. \r\n\r\nSome
    stories take him far back in time, and there is great food for thought in them
    all. Many destinations touch him. \r\n\r\nSome people think he is not a real
    pilgrim, others see him as just starting his journey. But he goes on, persistently,
    and completes the tasks given to him.\r\t"
  enOutroText: "Finally, Oliver has visited all the destinations on his list. He
    has seen and heard so much, and he realises that he no longer feels the urge
    to keep travelling. He just wants to stop, be quiet and think. He is in no hurry
    to go anywhere, he can rest where he is, take his time, to be here and now, among
    the beauty and sacredness. \r\nOliver is approached by an old man who looks like
    he has something to say or ask.\r\n\"I guess you've found it, then. Your treasure.\u201D\r\nOliver
    takes a closer look at the man and realises, blushing, that he is one of the
    two men from whom he stole the list of the destinations.\r\n\"No, I did not\",
    Oliver denies.\r\n\"Think again\", the man says and calmly takes a seat beside
    Oliver.\r\nOliver thinks and suddenly comes to realise that maybe this was the
    purpose of it all. \r\n\"You are right\", the man says: \"We saw you yearning
    for peace, and that is what you found. A true treasure. Now take your time and
    relish it. Then, give the list to someone else who needs it, whatever way you
    think best.\u201D\r"
